#)What is toString()?
toString() is a method in Java that returns a text (string) that describes an object.
Every class in Java gets this method from the Object class (because all classes inherit from it).

or

toString() is used to show object information as text instead of showing its memory address.

#)Why we use it?
We use toString() when we want to see the details of an object in a readable way ‚Äî like printing it using System.out.println().


#)Example (without overriding)
class Student {
    int id = 1;
    String name = "Adarsh";
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student();
        System.out.println(s1);
    }
}


üßæ Output:
Student@5ca881b5

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
we need to ovveride toStringMethod() then we are  able print object otehr wise print memory address 
which is hard to read.

Example (with overriding)
class Student {
    int id = 1;
    String name = "Adarsh";

    public String toString() {
        return "Student[id=" + id + ", name=" + name + "]";
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student();
        System.out.println(s1);
    }
}

üßæ Output:
Student[id=1, name=Adarsh]


